chunks.title: System Overview
chunks.text: System Overview The system is designed for clarity and traceability. It favors small surfaces, durable language, and documentation that can be reused. Updates are made in public and kept readable. The structure is intentionally simple so that future changes do not break the surface.

chunks.title: Fit Overview
chunks.text: Fit Overview Fit is about alignment with pace, ownership, and clarity. I work best with small teams that value written decisions, direct feedback, and outcomes that can be measured. Poor fit includes high-churn environments, unclear ownership, and work that prioritizes volume over quality. The goal is shared momentum, not just shared goals.

chunks.title: About Terence Brasch
chunks.text: About Terence Brasch Terence Brasch is a senior frontend engineer and creative technologist. He builds calm, high-performing interfaces and the systems behind them. His work spans in-person research environments and physical-digital products, with a focus on clarity, durability, and real-world constraints.

chunks.title: Goodies Overview
chunks.text: Goodies Overview Goodies is a small retail system that blends brand, operations, and technology. It focuses on clear inventory decisions, calm service flow, and practical tools that work in real conditions. The project treats the shop as a living lab. Feedback from customers and staff drives small, measured experiments that improve consistency without losing the human feel.

chunks.title: Fireside Overview
chunks.text: Fireside Overview Fireside is a small, in-person creative technology practice based in Portland. It is designed for focused work that needs real tools, real constraints, and clear decisions. The room is intentionally small to keep conversations precise and outcomes accountable. Sessions prioritize tangible artifacts: prototypes, diagrams, tests, and written decisions. The work is not about volume or spectacle. It is a quiet environment to translate complex ideas into usable, durable systems.
